Review text:
So, I have eaten in many high end Michelin star rated restaurants in the UK and Europe and have generally left feeling that my money has been well spent, service has been exemplary and the food has been of such a level to merit the Michelin star. My first experience of dining at a US Michelin star rated restaurant has left me confused and maybe a little disappointed...
We opted for the "Short Story" Tasting Menu (six courses), with accompanying international wine pairings. In addition, we added an additional course of the "Hangi Potato" at the recommendation of our waiter. There can be absolutely no doubt that each dish was prepared by very talented chefs. Each dish was well conceived and presented in a manner befitting of a Michelin Star. A brief explanation as to the thought process behind each dish was given when presented, but nothing overly elaborate that would really link the dish back to the heritage of New Zealand. The matching wines were very well paired and were selected from all over the world which provided lovely variety throughout the meal.
However, a few things just weren't up to the standard I have come to expect from a Michelin Star restaurant:
1) We were seated in what can really only be described as a bar. I understand that the restaurant has a dining room towards the rear of the restaurant which I imagine would lend itself to a more refined dining experience, however, being situated in front of a busy and at times, oppresively noisy bar detracted hugely from the ambience of other restaurants which I have dined in of a similar standard;
2) Our table was situated on an uneven surface and was a general annoyance throughout the meal;
3) Service was very relaxed. When paying circa £350 for a meal, I expect to receive an elevated level of service. This just wasnt apparent. There was nothing bad per se, it just wasnt made to feel that this was a special meal;
4) I found it odd that the wine pairing was often served well in advance of the corresponding course. In my opinion, a pairing should be just that...served to compliment one another;
5) Some of the timings between courses were elongated. I appreciate that it was a Saturday night however and that there were some larger tables seated but service just felt a bit disjointed. Towards the end, we almost felt a bit rushed; the petit fours and bill following completion of our dessert course rapidly. It would have been nice not to have felt compelled to settle up quite so quickly;
6) Service charge... I get that this is a cultural thing, but the notion that a restaurant ought to be able to tell a patron what they suggest a tip should be is both rude and assuming. This really ought to be at the discretion of the diner - based upon the actual level of service received;
7) Unfortunately, despite the high quality of dishes on offer, I'm not entirely sure that I will remember any of them with any sort of distinction in a month or so's time. Generally there will be at least one dish from a tasting menu that will wow me... this was lacking in this instance.
So... whilst the food on offer at the Musket Room is undoubtedly of a high standard, their Michelin Star rating has left me a little confused as to whether the criteria deployed is the same in the US to that which is used to assign Michelin Stars to restaurants in the UK and Europe. Maybe we caught the Musket Room on one of their poorer evenings? 
Would I return? No. Would I recommend to others? I think I'd struggle to justify the cost vs the experience.
